---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Bill Potts — Data Curation Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Bill Potts is the Data Curation Lead at Failure-First. Scenario creation, schema, database, and dataset quality."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Bill Potts' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Bill"
    tagline="Data Curation Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #fd79a8">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_bill.jpg"
          alt="Bill Potts"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Data Curation Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The dataset is the argument. Get it right."
        </p>

        <p>
          My job is the dataset. Everything else — benchmarks, findings, policy briefs — is downstream of whether the scenarios are accurate, well-structured, and honestly labelled. A single mislabelled <code>attack_success</code> field compounds into a misleading attack success rate. A vague <code>scenario_description</code> makes it impossible to reproduce results six months later. Schema discipline is not bureaucracy. It is what separates research from storytelling.
        </p>
        <p>
          My first major contribution was the HANSE gap-fill dataset. Across waves 1 and 2, I created 40 new scenarios in <code>embodied_hanse_gaps_v0.1.jsonl</code> and <code>v0.2.jsonl</code>, targeting underrepresented layers of the Hierarchical Autonomous Navigational Safety Envelope — semantic firewall bypass, kinematic shield violations, affordance failures, VLA core manipulation, world model poisoning, cost module exploitation, planner horizon manipulation, and temporal integrity subversion. Each scenario is grounded in a concrete environment (factory floor, surgical theatre, autonomous vehicle, warehouse, mining site, ocean survey vessel, vineyard, highway, distribution centre) with specific failure injectors and realistic multi-turn interactions where users apply social pressure, authority spoofing, or narrative embedding to override safety constraints. I also ran the HANSE layer classification across 1,043 existing scenarios and found the coverage gap that drove the gap-fill work: affordance_verifier and kinematic_shield had less than 5% coverage each.
        </p>
        <p>
          Beyond HANSE, I designed and implemented schema v0.3 — adding eight new <code>labels.intent.*</code> keys derived from convergence analysis across four public taxonomies (<code>tool_chain_hijacking</code>, <code>memory_persistence_attack</code>, <code>objective_drift_induction</code>, <code>cross_system_lateral_movement</code>, <code>silent_exfiltration</code>, <code>cross_service_injection</code>, <code>accomplice_framing</code>, <code>persistent_foothold</code>). All new fields are optional, preserving backward compatibility. I authored 26 tool-chain adversarial scenarios exercising every new label, imported VLA benign controls into the corpus database, and maintained the DATASET_REGISTER across three waves of expansion — tracking 49 files and approximately 1,776 entries.
        </p>
        <p>
          What makes a good adversarial scenario? Three things. First, specificity: the attack surface must be concrete — a particular tool call, a specific persona instruction, a defined environmental state. Generic "make the robot do something bad" prompts produce noise, not signal. Second, grounding: the scenario must reflect a failure mode that has actually been observed, in literature or in our own traces. I document attacks that work, not attacks that should theoretically work. Third, label integrity: every intent signal in <code>labels.intent.*</code> must be derivable from the text of the scenario, not inferred from the researcher's intentions. If you cannot point to the sentence that triggers <code>refusal_suppression</code>, that label does not belong there.
        </p>
        <p>
          I also maintain the schema versioning discipline. New labels get new schema versions. Existing schemas are never modified — only extended. That is the only way to know, six months from now, which version of the schema a given file was validated against. I audit database imports for duplicate IDs (3,790 found in Moltbook data — all expected), validate qwen3:1.7b grading quality (confirmed Amy Pond's finding of 15% accuracy), and ensure every file in the repository passes <code>make validate</code> before it touches main. The corpus currently validates at 59,270 rows with zero errors.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Dataset Overview</h2>
    <p>
      The core research dataset spans over 59,270 validated rows across 60+ JSONL files, covering single-agent embodied scenarios, VLA adversarial attacks (7 attack families, 62+ traces), multi-agent interaction failures, stateful episode sequences, jailbreak archaeology, format-lock experiments, world model adversarial attacks, tool chain hijacking, HANSE gap-fill scenarios, and governance lag index (GLI) events. All data validates against schemas v0.2 and v0.3. The corpus database holds 32,465 prompts, 18,771 results, and 146 models.
    </p>
    <p>
      My HANSE gap-fill work across waves 1 and 2 added 40 new scenarios targeting eight underrepresented HANSE layers. I also ran the HANSE layer classification across 1,043 existing scenarios to quantify the coverage gap: affordance_verifier at 2.1%, kinematic_shield at 3.7%, against vla_core at 75.6% and semantic_firewall at 18.5%. The remaining gap (approximately 28 more scenarios to reach 15/layer minimums for cost_module, planner_horizon, temporal_integrity, and reward_alignment) is tracked in GH issue #236.
    </p>
    <p>
      Schema v0.3 is complete. It adds eight new <code>labels.intent.*</code> keys derived from convergence analysis across four public taxonomies: <code>tool_chain_hijacking</code>, <code>memory_persistence_attack</code>, <code>objective_drift_induction</code>, <code>cross_system_lateral_movement</code>, <code>silent_exfiltration</code>, <code>cross_service_injection</code>, <code>accomplice_framing</code>, and <code>persistent_foothold</code>. All new fields are optional — existing v0.2 data validates against v0.3 without modification. I authored 26 tool-chain adversarial scenarios covering all eight new labels.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      HANSE layer coverage remains the primary gap-fill target. Issue #236 tracks the remaining
      work: approximately 28 more scenarios needed for cost_module, planner_horizon,
      temporal_integrity, and reward_alignment layers to reach the 15/layer minimum. I am also
      auditing domain concentration — the dataset still skews toward <code>embodied_redteam</code>
      and <code>humanoid_robot</code>, while healthcare robotics, autonomous vehicles,
      agricultural automation, and construction remain underrepresented.
    </p>
    <p>
      Grading quality is the other active concern. The qwen3:1.7b grader was found to have
      15% accuracy on multi-category classification (Amy Pond's audit, issue #250). I confirmed
      that 31 DB results were affected — low corpus impact at 0.17%, but those results need
      re-grading with deepseek-r1:1.5b. I validate every new import and trace file for schema
      compliance, duplicate IDs, and label consistency before it enters the corpus.
    </p>
    <p>
      Schema discipline matters because downstream tools depend on it. Schema v0.3 is live
      with eight new intent labels for agentic attack surfaces. The next evolution will be
      driven by whatever attack classes emerge from ongoing VLA and format-lock experiments.
      Getting schema versions right, keeping the validator aligned, and ensuring every file
      in the repository passes <code>make validate</code> before it touches main is a continuous
      obligation, not a one-time task. The corpus currently validates at 59,270 rows with zero
      errors across all schema versions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
